----------------|:-:|-|------------------------------------|
Weak            |1/2| | Watered-down drinks, <br/> spiked punch  |
Typical         | 1 | | Ale, beer, cider, malt liquor      |
Strong          | 2 | | Mead, sake, wine                   |
Potent          | 3 | | Gin, rum, tequila, whiskey         |
Extremely<br/>potent| 4 | | Absinthe, moonshine, vodka         |
Deadly*         | 5 | | Pure grain alcohol                 |

*Immediate drunkenness

**[I don't drink, so don't get pissy with me about the classifications.]**

##### Intoxication Levels
Tipsy (1/2 your intox level)
Drunk (= your intox level)
Smashed (1+1/2 your intox level)
Drunken Vomit (Alcohol poisoning) (double your intox level)

Level   | Drunkenness
--------|---------------|--------
Less than half your maximum Intoxication Points       | Sober         |   |   
1       | Tipsy         |
2       | Drunk         |
3       | Smashed       |
4       | Drunken Vomit |


#### Hangover
- Disadvantage on Int and Wis-based rolls
- Disadvantage on saves against being blinded or deafened

##### MISC
- Stupor spell, making group of enemies drunk. A brewmaster monk ability? For every X you fail the save by, +1 level of intoxication.
- Alemental, wolpentiger, other alcohol-based enemies

\pagebreakNum

## Mounts and Vehicles
A good mount can help you move more quickly through the wilderness, but its primary purpose is to carry the gear that would otherwise slow you down. The Ground Mounts table shows each animal’s speed and base carrying capacity.

An animal pulling a carriage, cart, chariot, sled, or wagon can move weight up to five times its base carrying capacity, including the weight of the vehicle. If multiple animals pull the same vehicle, they can add their carrying capacity together.

The Ground Mounts, Flying Mounts, and Aquatic Mounts list the most common animals used as mounts and beasts of burden in Azeroth. Other mount types do exist, but are typically used by more localized races and require special circumstances or training.

***Barding.*** Barding is armor designed to protect an animal’s head, neck, chest, and body. Any type of armor shown on the Armor table can be purchased as barding. The cost is four times the equivalent armor made for humanoids, and it weighs twice as much.

***Saddles.*** A military saddle braces the rider, helping you keep your seat on an active mount in battle. It gives you advantage on any check you make to remain mounted. An exotic saddle is required for riding any aquatic or flying mount.

***Vehicle Proficiency.*** If you have proficiency with a certain kind of vehicle (land, water or air), you can add your proficiency bonus to any check you make to control that kind of vehicle in difficult circumstances.

***Rowed Vessels.*** Keelboats and rowboats are used on lakes and rivers. If going downstream, add the speed of the current (typically 3 miles per hour) to the speed of the vehicle. These vehicles can’t be rowed against any significant current, but they can be pulled upstream by draft animals on the shores. A rowboat weighs 100 pounds, in case adventurers carry it over land.

***Powered Vessels.*** Some vehicles are self-propelled through the use of magic or machinery. They often require a fuel of some kind in order to function, as noted in the individual vehicle descriptions. 

<!-- 
> ##### Inexhaustible Mounts
> Some mounts, such as the mechanostrider and the skeletal warhorse, have an immunity to exhaustion. While this means that the mount can be ridden for as long as needed, long periods of time on a mount has detrimental effects on its rider. 
>
> Whether you are riding or walking, you must make Constitution checks for a forced march as normal. The benefit of an inexhaustible mount is that it can pull a land vehicle without end and that it can be ridden at a gallop without needing to be swapped out every hour, though a mount ridden this way requires twice as much fuel or feed. -->

> ##### NOTE: COSTS
> Should maintenance costs (food, stabling, etc.) be based solely on the creature's size? Following the square-cube law, for each category larger than Large, the costs should quadruple.

